    slug: "the-jinn-and-human-sickness",
    description: `The Jinn and Human Sickness is an informative and carefully researched Islamic book that addresses the often-misunderstood topic of the relationship between the world of jinn and physical or psychological ailments experienced by human beings. Published by Darussalam under the Education category, this book provides a balanced and authentic Islamic perspective on how jinn possession, evil eye (ayn), and magic (sihr) may affect human health, while firmly grounding its discussion in the Quran, authentic Sunnah, and the established methodology of orthodox Islamic scholarship. The book begins by presenting the Islamic belief in the existence of jinn as a creation of Allah made from smokeless fire, possessing free will, intellect, and the ability to interact with the human world. It clarifies what the Quran and authentic hadith say about jinn — their nature, their capabilities, their limitations, and the Islamic ruling on seeking protection from their harm. The author takes great care to distinguish between authentic Islamic teachings and the many cultural superstitions, myths, and exaggerated claims that have become associated with this topic in various Muslim communities. The Jinn and Human Sickness discusses the symptoms that Islamic scholars have identified as potential indicators of jinn-related affliction, while simultaneously emphasising that many physical and psychological conditions have purely natural causes and should first be treated through conventional medical means. The book presents the Islamic method of dealing with jinn-related issues, which is based entirely on the Quran and Prophetic supplications — including specific verses and surahs known for their protective and healing properties (such as Ayat al-Kursi, Surah Al-Falaq, Surah An-Nas, and the opening verses of Surah Al-Baqarah), the dua for protection taught by Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him), and the guidelines for legitimate ruqyah (spiritual healing). The book warns against the numerous un-Islamic practices, fraudulent healers, and superstitious rituals that have no basis in the Sharia and may in fact be harmful. It stresses the importance of strengthening one's faith, maintaining regular prayer, reciting the morning and evening adhkar, and placing complete trust in Allah as the most effective means of protection against all forms of harm. This book is a valuable resource for those seeking authentic Islamic knowledge on a sensitive topic that is often surrounded by misinformation and exploitation.`,
